      "type": "action",
      "tool": "websearch",
      "code": "{\"query\": \"Particle Health Epic antitrust lawsuit data access interoperability healthcare\", \"numResults\": 5, \"type\": \"deep\"}",
      "output": "{\n  \"search_id\": \"search_a20727b73b0043b891bea7e6065e9899\",\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.veronapress.com/news/startup-particle-health-files-antitrust-lawsuit-against-epic-systems/article_ca949d16-7c3e-11ef-9206-53191935c7ed.html\",\n      \"title\": \"Startup Particle Health files antitrust lawsuit against Epic Systems | Local News | veronapress.com\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-09-26\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"They claim that over the past six months, Epic has cut off access to data for Particle’s customers, made discredited complaints and overwhelmed Particle’s support operations by “stoking baseless security concerns.”\\n\\nQuinn Emanuel Urquhart & Sullivan, LLP filed the lawsuit on behalf of Particle Health in a New York federal court on Monday, Sept. 23. The suit seeks an adjudication that Epic has violated the Sherman Act, an 1890 law that prohibits activities restricting competition in the marketplace.\\n\\nParticle Health is also seeking monetary damages and injunctive relief that requires Epic to cease anticompetitive conduct.\\n\\n“Our health care system stands at a crossroads,” Prestinario said in the release. “Timely and complete medical information is critical to effective care. Regrettably, Epic is hoarding the data, showing how it can rapidly seize control of all markets that depend on the clinical records that rightfully belong to patients.”\\nA spokesperson from Epic described Particle Health’s claims as “baseless” in an email statement to the Press.\\n\\n“This lawsuit attempts to divert attention from the real issue: Particle’s unlawful actions on the Carequality health information exchange network violated HIPAA privacy regulations. Particle’s complaint mischaracterizes Carequality’s decision, which in fact proposes banning Particle customers that were accessing patient data for impermissible purposes. Epic’s software is open and interoperable, allowing healthcare organizations to easily share data under HIPAA and all relevant regulations. Epic will continue to protect patient privacy and vigorously defend itself against Particle’s meritless claims.”\\n\\nContact reporter Maddie Bergstrom at mbergstrom@orourkemediagroup.com\\n\\n* [Facebook](https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.veronapress.\\ncom%2Fnews%2Fstartup-particle-health-files-antitrust-lawsuit-against-epic-systems%2Farticle_ca949d16-7c3e-11ef-9206-53191935c7ed.html%3Futm_medium%3Dsocial%26utm_source%3Dfacebook%26utm_campaign%3Duser-share \\\"Share on Facebook\\\")\\n* [Twitter](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?&text=Startup%20Particle%20Health%20files%20antitrust%20lawsuit%20against%20Epic%20Systems&via=veronapress&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.veronapress.com%2Fnews%2Fstartup-particle-health-files-antitrust-lawsuit-against-epic-systems%2Farticle_ca949d16-7c3e-11ef-9206-53191935c7ed.html%3Futm_medium%3Dsocial%26utm_source%3Dtwitter%26utm_campaign%3Duser-share \\\"Tweet\\\")\\n* [WhatsApp](https://wa.me/?text=https://www.veronapress.com/news/startup-particle-health-files-antitrust-lawsuit-against-epic-systems/article_ca949d16-7c3e-11ef-9206-53191935c7ed.html \\\"WhatsApp\\\")\\n* Email\\n* Print\\n* Copy article link\\n* Save\\n\\n[Maddie Bergstrom](https://www.veronapress.com/users/profile/Maddie%20Bergstrom)\\n\\n#### [Maddie Bergstrom](https://www.veronapress.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.fiercehealthcare.com/health-tech/startup-particle-health-files-antitrust-lawsuit-against-epic-alleging-it-uses-monopoly\",\n      \"title\": \"Particle Health takes on Epic in antitrust lawsuit\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-09-23\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"com/publiceditorial.qtxasset.com/2024-09-23+Particle+Health+Complaint.pdf) (PDF), filed today, alleges Epic engaged in monopolistic, anti-competitive practices, using its \\\"power over EHRs to expand its dominance into the fledgling market for payer platforms,\\\" according to the lawsuit, which was reviewed by Fierce Healthcare.\\n\\n\\\"Epic has used its position of dominance to worm its way to the core of the U.S. healthcare system and stamp out competition in a wide variety of interrelated markets, thereby generating billions of dollars for itself,\\\" Particle claimed in the complaint.\\n\\nParticle Health argues in its federal complaint that Epic has not only engaged in anticompetitive behavior but has purposefully blocked the exchange of patient information.\\n\\nIn an emailed response to Fierce Healthcare, an Epic spokesperson said Particle’s claims are baseless.\\n\\\"This lawsuit attempts to divert attention from the real issue: Particle’s unlawful actions on the Carequality health information exchange network violated HIPAA [Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act] privacy regulations. Particle’s complaint mischaracterizes Carequality’s decision, which in fact proposes banning Particle customers that were accessing patient data for impermissible purposes,\\\" the Epic spokesperson said.\\n\\n\\\"Epic’s software is open and interoperable, allowing healthcare organizations to easily share data under HIPAA and all relevant regulations. Epic will continue to protect patient privacy and vigorously defend itself against Particle’s meritless claims,\\\" the spokesperson said.\\n\\nThe suit seeks an adjudication that Epic has violated the Sherman Act as well as monetary damages and injunctive relief compelling Epic to cease its anticompetitive conduct.\\n\\\"Epic is using its monopoly power over electronic health records (EHRs) to bar Particle from the fledgling payer platform market —just one example of Epic plotting to 'snuff out' competition in new markets that leverage medical records,\\\" Particle Health executives said in a [press release](https://www.particlehealth.com/blog/epic-systems-stranglehold-on-u-s-medical-records-harms-patient-care-lawsuit) .\\n\\n“Epic Systems controls the medical information of nearly every American—meaning one private company has unchecked power over our health care,” said Particle Health CEO Jason Prestinario in a statement. “Now, Epic is using that power to thwart an emerging industry intended to bring payers and providers into closer collaboration for better patient care.”\\n\\nWith a 36% market share of the hospital sector, Epic is a dominant force in the health IT industry. Particle Health claims that Epic controls the health information of up to 94% of Americans.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://healthexec.com/topics/healthcare-management/legal-news/epic-sued-interoperability-startup-following-dispute-over-patient-data\",\n      \"title\": \"Epic sued by interoperability startup following dispute over patient data\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-09-25\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"* Care\\n  \\n  Back | Care\\n  \\n    + Care Delivery\\n    + Covid-19\\n    + Digital Transformation\\n    + Telehealth\\n* Data\\n  \\n  Back | Data\\n  \\n    + Artificial Intelligence\\n    + Cybersecurity\\n    + EMR/EHR\\n    + Informatics\\n* Videos\\n* Conferences\\n  \\n  Back | Conferences\\n  \\n    + AHA\\n    + AMA\\n    + CHIME\\n    + HFMA\\n    + HIMSS\\n    + MGMA\\n* Custom Content\\n  \\n  Back | Custom Content\\n  \\n    + Experience Stories\\n    + Webinars & Videos\\n* Subscribe\\n\\n[](https://twitter.com/hlthexec/ \\\"Twitter Icon\\\") [](https://www.facebook.com/HealthExecTMG/ \\\"Facebook Icon\\\") [](https://www.linkedin.com/company/health-exec/ \\\"Linkedin Icon\\\") [](https://vimeo.com/innovatehealthcare \\\"Linkedin Icon\\\")\\n\\n## Search form\\n\\nSearch\\n\\nHome\\n\\n# Epic sued by interoperability startup following dispute over patient data\\n\\nChad Van Alstin | September 24, 2024 | Health Exec | Legal News\\n\\nThe Epic EMR booth at HIMSS 2023. Photo by Dave Fornell\\nMedical record interoperability startup Particle Health has filed a lawsuit against Epic Systems, accusing the electronic health record (EHR) king of violating federal antitrust laws. Particle claims Epic’s business practices allow it to unfairly control patient records, which negatively impacts companies attempting to improve the exchange of important medical information.\\n\\nIn an [announcement](https://www.particlehealth.com/blog/epic-systems-stranglehold-on-u-s-medical-records-harms-patient-care-lawsuit) , Particle accused Epic of monopolistic practices by “using its dominance in the EHR market to prevent competition in the payer platform market.” The interoperability startup argued healthcare payer records are key to developing “scalable systems for analyzing health records” that could then be used to improve patient care.\\n\\nParticle, which was founded in 2018, entered the payer platform market in 2023.\\nEarlier this year, Epic stopped providing Particle users access to patient data from its Carequality exchange, arguing the requests posed privacy and security risks due to the startup allegedly sharing data with third-parties not involved in patient care.\\n\\nThe dispute has been going on for the last six months, Particle said, adding its lawsuit aims to disincentivize Epic from continuing to cut off companies who rely on access to patient data. Particle stated it believes Epic was acting maliciously to “squash” the company and “snuff out” other competitors by denying requests for data access.\\n\\n## Subscribe to Health Exec News\\n\\nEmail Address \\\\*\\n\\n#### Epic has data from almost everyone\\n\\nEpic has long dominated the EHR market. In 2023, it was the only vendor to [increase its cumulative customer base](https://healthexec.com/topics/healthcare-management/mergers-and-acquisitions/epic-ehr-market-klas-report) . An estimated 94% of all patients in the U.S.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.fiercehealthcare.com/health-tech/particle-healths-antitrust-lawsuit-against-epic-moves-forward-after-judge-dismisses\",\n      \"title\": \"Antitrust lawsuit against Epic moves forward, judge rules\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2025-08-09\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Epic, Particle Health dispute exposes broader challenges with sharing patient data, health IT experts say\\n\\nIn her ruling on the motion to dismiss, Keeler noted, Buchwald limited discovery to three questions: Who counts as a payer versus a payvider? What exactly do Epic’s and Particle’s products do (retrieval, storage, analytics)? What alternatives are available to payers?\\n\\n\\\"In other words, no fishing expedition into Epic’s broader conduct until market definition is nailed down (which is the real unlock for Particle to get to). This is huge and flips it from 'big Particle win' to 'Particle survives,'\\\" Keeler wrote.\\n\\nIn her ruling, Buchwald also voiced skepticism about Particle Health's claim on market definition. \\\"This disagreement regarding one of the foundational facts in this case—whether the parties’ products perform the same basic functions—is frustrating,\\\" the judge wrote in the ruling.\\nAccording to Bill Russell, a health IT executive and founder of This Week Health, healthcare antitrust cases typically favor defendants when market definition is disputed, he [wrote](https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7369912727697514496/) in a LinkedIn post.\\n\\n### How the feud between Epic, Particle Health unfolded\\n\\nParticle's lawsuit, in part, stems from developments in the spring of 2024 and [growing tensions](https://www.fiercehealthcare.com/health-tech/epic-particle-health-dispute-exposes-broader-issues-accessing-and-sharing-patient-data) between the two companies over access and use of patients' clinical data. The dispute centered on who is accessing patients' health data, for what purposes and the proper gatekeeping process to safeguard medical data.\\nBoth Epic and Particle are connected to Carequality, which operates a nationwide health data exchange service used by more than 600,000 care providers, 50,000 clinics and 4,200 hospitals to access patients’ medical records. Carequality says it supports the exchange of 1 billion clinical documents each month.\\n\\nEpic filed a formal dispute with Carequality in March 2024, claiming that Particle was sharing patient data with some companies that were then using the data for reasons unrelated to treatment. \\\"This poses potential security and privacy risks, including the potential for HIPAA Privacy Rule violations in the event disclosures of protected health information were made under the Treatment Permitted Purpose when the requesting entities did not have treatment relationships with the patients to whom the records related,” Epic said in the notice to its customers, which was viewed by Fierce Healthcare.\\n\\n### Related\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.fiercehealthcare.com/health-tech/epic-hit-lawsuit-cureis-healthcare-alleged-scheme-destroy-its-business\",\n      \"title\": \"CureIS Healthcare sues Epic alleging anti-competitive practices\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2025-05-17\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"com/health-tech/real-time-medical-systems-scores-win-information-blocking-lawsuit-against) that electronic health records company PointClickCare can't block health analytics firm RTMS from accessing patient data from its skilled nursing facility customers.\\n\\nKeeler, a health IT expert who has been following the cases closely, said in a [post on LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/brendan-keeler_the-new-court-case-cureis-healthcare-v-activity-7328516501471219714-5yLd/?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_desktop&rcm=ACoAAALHHeYBWofXJXyjuWDaWbfKfW11c2Q4bio) that the outcome of the CureIS-Epic lawsuit could have implications for all EHR vendors and ongoing friction with point solution vendors.\\n\\n\\\"The real solution for EHRs? Rapid reorientation towards headlessness, openness, and equal competition with third parties. It is a harder road and it is a cultural shift. But the headwinds are overwhelmingly strong in any other direction,\\\" Keeler wrote on LinkedIn.\\nCureIS claims that the \\\"why\\\" behind Epic’s alleged misconduct is clear. \\\"Epic is nearing the saturation point in EHR software and needs to identify new areas for growth,\\\" the company wrote in its complaint.\\n\\nThe company said what initially seemed like one-off instances of friction with Epic were, in fact, part of a \\\"widespread scheme by Epic to improperly interfere with CureIS’s business, as well as that of other providers of MCDR software.\\\"\\n\\nCureIS points out that Epic has massive market power and alleges that the company is using its dominance in the market to stifle smaller innovators, which limits choices for healthcare organizations. Epic commands 42.3% of the acute care EHR market, according to [KLAS Research](https://www.fiercehealthcare.com/health-tech/epic-gaining-more-ground-hospital-ehr-market-share-widens-its-lead-over-oracle-health) . More than [325 million patients](https://www.epic.com/about/) have a current electronic record in Epic, according to the health IT company.\\n“CureIS was founded to address the chronic inefficiencies plaguing government-managed care programs. Epic’s playbook—prioritizing market control over transparency, accountability, and performance—is philosophically antithetical to our mission,\\\" CureIS CEO Chris Sawotin said in a [statement.](https://cureis.com/cureis-files-lawsuit-against-epic-alleging-monopolistic-conduct-libel-and-data-blocking/)\\n\\nEpic lawsuit Competition electronic health records (EHRs) Digital Health Finance Hospitals Practices Providers Health Tech\\n\\nHome\\n\\n[](https://www.linkedin.com/showcase/fierce-healthcare/) [](https://www.facebook.com/FierceHealthcare/) [](https://twitter.com/FierceHealth)\\n\\n* Connect\\n  \\n    + The Team\\n    + [Advertise](https://healthcarelifesciences.questex.com/healthcare/ \\\"Advertise With Us\\\")\\n    + [Marketing Kit](https://healthcarelifesciences.questex.com/marketing-kit/)\\n    + [Let's Talk](https://healthcarelifesciences.questex.com/lets-talk/)\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.healthcareitnews.com/news/judge-denies-full-dismissal-particles-antitrust-case-against-epic\",\n      \"title\": \"Judge denies full dismissal of Particle's antitrust case ...\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2025-09-09\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"\\\"This is the first time in Epic's history that an antitrust case against them has gotten to this point,\\\" said Particle Health CEO Jason Prestinario in a statement emailed to _Healthcare IT News_ last week. \\\"It's the next step to a bigger victory for better patient care and more patient control of their medical info!\\\"\\n\\n\\\"The Court dismissed the majority of Particle’s claims,\\\" an Epic spokesperson said by email on Friday. \\\"The ruling included the observation that Carequality’s 'imposition of the corrective action plan [on Particle] was entirely reasonable.'\\n\\n\\\"Epic has worked and will continue to work to protect the privacy of patients' data. We look forward to the opportunity to present evidence to prevail on the remaining claims.\\\"  \\n  \\n**THE LARGER TREND**\\n\\nEpic [filed to dismiss](https://www.healthcareitnews.\\ncom/news/epic-files-dismiss-antitrust-lawsuit) the antitrust lawsuit in December, calling the case retribution for confronting Particle for enabling some of its customers to obtain confidential patient medical records under pretenses on the Carequality health information exchange network.\\n\\nThe court battle highlights how trust in national health information exchange can be easily broken and patient privacy under HIPAA can be shirked. Epic said that because endpoints that are not HIPAA-covered entities may request and exchange data, it might lead some health systems to consider forgoing participation in that network, under the [Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement](https://www.healthcareitnews.com/news/tefca-live-and-ready-exchange-data-says-hhs) .\\n\\nParticle founder Troy Bannister had said on social media when the company filed its suit that despite Epic disconnecting providers on a \\\"massive scale\\\" without warning, Particle would [remain](https://www.particlehealth.\\ncom/blog/particle-health-affirms-ongoing-connectivity-with-epic-systems-and-refutes-recent-reports) [connected](https://www.particlehealth.com/blog/particle-health-affirms-ongoing-connectivity-with-epic-systems-and-refutes-recent-reports) to the HIE framework.\\n\\nEpic, however, insisted the [Carequality resolution](https://www.healthcareitnews.com/news/epic-and-particle-health-continue-spar-over-data-exchange-dispute) , released to the public the month after the lawsuit was filed, showed it did not treat Particle Health any differently in reviewing its connections under HIPAA. It had dismissed providers perceived to be using a masked gateway when making their patient health information requests, which could indicate a potential HIPAA breach and would qualify for investigation under TEFCA and Carequality.\\n\\nHowever, Particle said Carequality's dispute resolution showed that the construct of the gateways was simply a matter of interpretation of Carequality's technical requirements.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.healthcarefinancenews.com/news/data-startup-particle-health-sues-epic-over-antitrust-concerns\",\n      \"title\": \"Data startup Particle Health sues Epic over antitrust concerns | Healthcare Finance News\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2025-10-16\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Startup company Particle Health, an intelligent data platform that aggravates patient data and sends it to healthcare companies, has [filed an antitrust lawsuit](https://hitconsultant.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/2024-09-23-Particle-Health-Complaint.pdf) against Epic Systems saying the electronic health record giant is using its market position to quash competition in the payer platform sector.\\n\\nFiled today in the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of New York, the lawsuit alleges that Epic violated the Sherman Act, which prevents unfair competition, by stopping Particle from entering into the still nascent payer platform market.\\n\\nIn addition to monetary damages, Particle is asking for a court order to make Epic stop its current practices.\\n\\n\\\"Epic Systems controls the medical information of nearly every American – meaning one private company has unchecked power over our healthcare,\\\" said Particle CEO Jason Prestinario.\\n\\\"Now, Epic is using that power to thwart an emerging industry intended to bring payers and providers into closer collaboration for better patient care.\\\"\\n\\n**WHAT'S THE IMPACT?**\\n\\nThe emerging payer platform market is intended to make data analysis in healthcare more modern and attuned to patients' care needs. The goal of the payer platform market is to ditch old-fashioned, paper-based processes in favor of efficient, scalable systems that can predict patient risk, analyze records and assist with clinical care decisions.\\n\\nThe lawsuit alleges Epic took actions that stifled Particle's ability to exchange health information. Over the past six months, according to the suit, Epic cut off data access for Particle customers and flooded the company's support staff with security concerns Particle considered \\\"baseless.\\\"\\n\\nAccording to the lawsuit, Epic's \\\"manipulation\\\" of EHR access is already having negative consequences for doctors and patients.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/healthcare-information-technology/ehrs/epic-denies-all-claims-in-particle-health-antitrust-lawsuit-6-updates/\",\n      \"title\": \"Epic denies all claims in Particle Health antitrust lawsuit ...\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2025-11-06\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"* [EHRs / Interoperability](https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/healthcare-information-technology/ehrs/)\\n* [Health IT](https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/healthcare-information-technology/)\\n\\n# Epic denies all claims in Particle Health antitrust lawsuit: 6 updates\\n\\nAdvertisement\\n\\nBy: Naomi Diaz\\n\\nThursday, November 6th, 2025\\n\\nPrint\\n\\nShare\\n\\n* [Click to share on Facebook (Opens in new window)](https://facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.beckershospitalreview.com%2Fhealthcare-information-technology%2Fehrs%2Fepic-denies-all-claims-in-particle-health-antitrust-lawsuit-6-updates%2F \\\"Click to share on Facebook\\\")\\n* [Click to share on X (Opens in new window)](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet/?text=Epic%20denies%20all%20claims%20in%20Particle%20Health%20antitrust%20lawsuit%3A%206%20updates&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.beckershospitalreview.com%2Fhealthcare-information-technology%2Fehrs%2Fepic-denies-all-claims-in-particle-health-antitrust-lawsuit-6-updates%2F&hashtags= \\\"Click to share on X\\\")\\n* [Click to share on LinkedIn (Opens in new window)](https://www.linkedin.com/sharing/share-offsite/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.beckershospitalreview.com%2Fhealthcare-information-technology%2Fehrs%2Fepic-denies-all-claims-in-particle-health-antitrust-lawsuit-6-updates%2F \\\"Click to share on LinkedIn\\\")\\n* Click to email a link to a friend (Opens in new window)\\n\\nEpic Systems has [filed](https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/69184842/53/particle-health-inc-v-epic-systems-corporation/) its formal response to Particle Health’s antitrust lawsuit, denying all allegations that it engaged in anticompetitive conduct or defamation against the health data exchange startup.\\n\\nNew York City-based Particle Health [sued](https://www.beckershospitalreview.com/healthcare-information-technology/ehrs/epic-faces-antitrust-lawsuit/) the Verona, Wis.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.fiercehealthcare.com/health-tech/epic-hits-back-particle-health-counter-argument-it-pushes-get-antitrust-case-dismissed\",\n      \"title\": \"Epic, Particle Health continue to spar over antitrust case\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"# Epic hits back at Particle Health counterargument as it pushes to get antitrust case dismissed\\n\\nBy Heather Landi Jan 28, 2025 4:40am\\n\\nEpic Particle Health antitrust lawsuit\\n\\nlaw and order concept In response to Epic's latest court filing, a Particle Health spokesperson said, \\\"We remain confident in the strength of the case and that our claims will survive the motion.\\\" (iStock / Getty Images Plus)\\n\\nIt continues to be a war of words—in the form of legal filings—between Epic and Particle Health as the startup fights to keep its antitrust lawsuit moving forward.\\n\\nHealth tech company Particle [filed](https://www.fiercehealthcare.com/health-tech/startup-particle-health-files-antitrust-lawsuit-against-epic-alleging-it-uses-monopoly) an antitrust lawsuit against Epic in September in the Southern District of New York alleging that the electronic health record giant is trying to muscle out competition.\\nParticle is a data platform that aggregates health information for digital health companies through APIs, providing access to more than 300 million patients’ medical records. With a 36% market share of the hospital sector, EHR giant Epic is a dominant force in the health IT industry.\\n\\nStarting last year, Particle expanded its services to payers to assist so-called \\\"pay-viders\\\" with accessing patients records for “secondary” purposes more typically associated with health insurance, like population health analytics or processing claims, which is allowed under HIPAA and the rules of health information networks, Particle said in its lawsuit.\\n\\nThe 81-page [lawsuit](https://s3.amazonaws.com/publiceditorial.qtxasset.com/2024-09-23+Particle+Health+Complaint.pdf) (PDF) alleges Epic engaged in monopolistic, anticompetitive practices, using its \\\"power over EHRs to expand its dominance into the fledgling market for payer platforms,\\\" according to the lawsuit.\\n\\n...\\n\\nBut, Keeler, a self-described advocate for interoperability and healthcare integration, said Particle still does not adequately explain why companies like Datavant and InterSystems that appear to offer similar services should be excluded from market definition.\\n\\nKeeler said he expected the court will rule for dismissal with leave to allow Particle to amend its lawsuit.\\n\\nFriday evening, Epic filed its final reply to support its attempt to have the court throw out Particle's antitrust lawsuit. The company doubled down on its argument that Particle makes \\\"fatally deficient claims\\\" in its lawsuit and in its opposition to Epic's motion to dismiss.\\n\\n### Related\\n\\nStartup Particle Health files antitrust lawsuit against Epic alleging it uses monopoly power to block competition\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.healthleadersmedia.com/ceo/latest-epic-case-exposes-next-interoperability-challenge-governance\",\n      \"title\": \"Latest Epic Case Exposes the Next Interoperability ...\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-03-11\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Those policies forced vendors and providers to make patient data more accessible across platforms and exchange networks.\\n\\nBut while technical interoperability has advanced rapidly, governance mechanisms have lagged behind.\\n\\n### What it means for leadership\\n\\nFor CIOs, the issue is increasingly operational. Health systems are now connected to multiple national networks that allow external organizations to request patient data for treatment, payment, and operations. Each connection expands the surface area for potential misuse if identity verification and access monitoring are not sufficiently robust.\\n\\nHealthcare technology leaders are already recognizing that governance must evolve alongside innovation. As one health system technology executive explained in a **[recent HealthLeaders interview](https://www.healthleadersmedia.com/innovation/how-balance-ai-adoption-governance?utm_source=chatgpt.com)** on responsible AI development, governance cannot be isolated within a single team.\\n“You cannot have one single group squirreled away trying to perfect data,” said Duke Health Chief Health Information Officer Eric Poon. “It needs to be a team sport.”\\n\\nThat principle increasingly applies to interoperability as well. Data governance is shifting from a purely technical function to an enterprise-wide responsibility spanning IT, compliance, legal, clinical leadership, and cybersecurity.\\n\\nThe Epic–Health Gorilla dispute also arrives as broader tensions around data access and competition intensify. Epic is currently defending a separate antitrust lawsuit from data platform Particle Health, which alleges the EHR vendor used its market position to restrict competitors’ access to patient data.\\n\\nThat case, which a federal judge allowed to proceed last year, reflects a parallel debate about whether dominant platforms control too much of the healthcare data ecosystem.\\n\\nTogether, these disputes highlight a fundamental challenge for the industry.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"warnings\": null,\n  \"usage\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"sku_search\",\n      \"count\": 1\n    }\n  ],\n  \"session_id\": \"ses_0cba093c2ffeCsX4cK31TWSMpy\"\n}",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1783290121677
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "websearch",
      "code": "{\"query\": \"21st Century Cures Act information blocking rule ONC interoperability FHIR mandate\", \"numResults\": 5, \"type\": \"deep\"}",
      "output": "{\n  \"search_id\": \"search_03e18609a46d4cb18a4fb26ff4c0ca33\",\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.healthit.gov/information-blocking/\",\n      \"title\": \"Information Blocking - ONC - Office of the National ...\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2026-04-08\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"ONC has authority to review claims of possible information blocking against health IT developers of certified health IT that may constitute a non-conformity under the ONC Health IT Certification Program. Separately, the HHS OIG has authority to investigate claims of possible information blocking across all types of actors: health care providers, health information networks and health information exchanges, and health IT developers of certified health IT.\\n\\n#### File an Information Blocking Claim Online\\n\\n[Visit Portal](https://healthit.gov/report-info-blocking)\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n#### Understand the Claims Review Process\\n\\n[View Process](https://healthit.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Information-Blocking-Portal-Process.pdf)\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n#### See Information Blocking Claim Data\\n\\n[View Data](https://healthit.gov/data/quickstats/information-blocking-claims-numbers/)\\n\\n* * *\\n\\n#### View the September 2025 Enforcement Alert\\n\\n[View Alert](https://healthit.gov/information-blocking/enforcement-alert/)\\n\\n* * *\\n## Information Blocking Provider Disincentives\\n\\nThe U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) released a final rule establishing disincentives for health care providers found by the HHS Office of Inspector General (OIG) to have committed information blocking. This implements the HHS Secretary’s authority under section 4004 of the 21st Century Cures Act (Cures Act) to establish “disincentives” for providers who knowingly and unreasonably interfere with the access, exchange, or use of electronic health information (EHI) except as required by law or covered by a regulatory exception.\\n\\n* ### Final Rule\\n  \\n  [Go to Federal Register](https://www.federalregister.gov/public-inspection/2024-13793/21st-century-cures-act-establishment-of-disincentives-for-health-care-providers-that-have-committed)\\n* ### Disincentives Final Rule Overview\\n  \\n  [Download Fact Sheet](https://healthit.gov/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Disincentives-Final-Rule-Overview-Fact-Sheet.pdf)\\n* ### Common Questions\\n  \\n  [Download Fact Sheet](https://healthit.gov/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/Disincentives-Common-Questions-Fact-Sheet.pdf)\\n\\n## Information Blocking Resources\\n\\n* Fact Sheets\\n* Blogs\\n* Webinars & Presentations\\n* Press & Media\\n\\nBlog [App Registration, Delay No More](https://healthit.gov/blog/information-blocking/app-registration-delay-no-more/)\\n\\n[Avinash Shanbhag](https://healthit.gov/profile/avinash-shanbhag/ \\\"View Avinash Shanbhag's Profile\\\")\\n\\n[Avinash Shanbhag](https://healthit.gov/profile/avinash-shanbhag/ \\\"View Avinash Shanbhag's Profile\\\")\\n\\nDec. 19, 2024 • 4 min read\\n\\nBlog [Unveiling the Redesigned SITE: A Unified Testing Hub for Health IT Developers](https://healthit.gov/blog/information-blocking/unveiling-the-redesigned-site-a-unified-testing-hub-for-health-it-developers/)\\n\\n[Erin Little](https://healthit.gov/profile/erin-little/ \\\"View Erin Little's Profile\\\")\\n\\n[Erin Little](https://healthit.gov/profile/erin-little/ \\\"View Erin Little's Profile\\\")\\n\\nDec.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.texmed.org/21stCCA\",\n      \"title\": \"21st Century Cures Act: Interoperability and Information Blocking\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"The Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology (ONC) released a final rule, _[21st Century Cures Act: Interoperability, Information Blocking, and the ONC Health IT Certification Program](https://www.healthit.gov/curesrule/)_ in May 2020.\\n* ### Final Rule\\n  \\n    + [**ONC's Cures Act Final Rule**](https://www.healthit.gov/curesrule/)\\n    + **[CMS Interoperability and Patient Access final rule](https://www.cms.gov/Regulations-and-Guidance/Guidance/Interoperability/index)**\\n* ### What is electronic health information (EHI)?\\n  \\n  EHI is defined as the electronic protected health information (ePHI) in a designated record set (as defined in the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) regulations) regardless of whether the records are used or maintained by or for a covered entity.\\n* ### Who are the “actors” covered by information blocking?\\n  \\n    + Physicians and Other Health Care Providers\\n+ Health Information Networks (HIN)/Health Information Exchanges (HIE)\\n    + Health IT Developer of Certified Health IT\\n* ### When do I have to comply with the information blocking requirement?\\n  \\n    + Actors are subject to the information blocking rule as of **April 5, 2021** . Although, you are already required to share EHI if you participate in the Promoting Interoperability of the Merit-Based Incentive Payment System (MIPS) program.\\n* ### What EHI must be shared?\\n  \\n  The information blocking provisions require that patients and their physicians be given immediate electronic access to significant portions of the patient’s EHI upon request, [unless an exception](https://www.healthit.gov/cures/sites/default/files/cures/2020-03/InformationBlockingExceptions.pdf) applies. This includes the information detailed in the [United States Core Data for Interoperability (USCDI) version 1](https://www.healthit.\\ngov/isa/united-states-core-data-interoperability-uscdi) data set and does include clinical notes and specifies eight note types:\\n  \\n    + Discharge summaries\\n    + History and physicals\\n    + Progress notes\\n    + Consult notes\\n    + Imaging reports\\n    + Laboratory reports\\n    + Pathology reports\\n    + Procedure notes\\n* ### I don't use an Electronic Health Record (EHR). Does this mean I have to get one?\\n  \\n  The requirements of the 21st Century Cures Act only applies to electronic patient health information. If you are using paper records, it will not apply to you. There is no mandate for you to move to an EHR.\\n* ### Can I charge for releasing patient medical records electronically?\\n  \\n  It depends. Read the details in the following member resources.\\n  \\n    + 21st Century Cures Act White Paper (March 2021)\\n    + White paper resource: Fees for Copies of Medical Records\\n* ### Resources\\n  \\n    + - [Interoperability and Patient Access Fact Sheet](https://www.cms.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://retinacarespecialists.com/21st-century-cures-act-no-information-blocking\",\n      \"title\": \"21st Century Cures Act: No Information Blocking\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2023-08-02\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Skip to main menu Skip to main content Skip to footer\\n\\n# 21st Century Cures Act: No Information Blocking\\n\\n[Home](https://retinacarespecialists.com/) > 21st Century Cures Act: No Information Blocking\\n\\nRetina Care Specialists is committed to making Electronic Health Information (EHI) available and for use that is authorized and permitted in accordance with applicable law.\\n\\nOur “No Information Blocking Policy” focuses on giving patients access to their EHI without creating unnecessary barriers. This Policy also helps deter the information blocking faced by healthcare providers when attempting to provide continuity of care for patients.\\n\\nFinally, our policy recognizes the eight (8) exceptions under the 21st Century Cures Act that identify reasonable and necessary practices and activities that do not constitute information blocking. Your Provider and/or Retina Care Specialists may, where allowed by law, interfere with access to EHI under the following (8) exceptions:\\n**Five (5) exceptions that allow us to not fulfill requests to access, exchange, or use EHI:**\\n\\n1. **Preventing harm exception** : taking actions that are reasonable and necessary to prevent harm to a patient or another person, provided certain conditions are met (45 CFR § 171.201).\\n\\n1. **Privacy exception** : not fulfilling a request to access, exchange, or use EHI to protect an individual’s privacy, provided certain conditions are met (45 CFR § 171.202).\\n\\n1. **Security exception** : interfering with the access, exchange, or use of EHI to protect the security of EHI, provided certain conditions are met (45 CFR § 171.203).\\n\\n1. **Infeasibility exception** not fulfilling a request to access, exchange, or use EHI due to the infeasibility of the request, provided certain conditions are met (45 CFR § 171.204).\\n\\n1.\\n**Health IT performance exception** : taking reasonable and necessary measures to make health IT temporarily unavailable or to degrade the health IT’s performance for the benefit of the overall performance of the health IT, provided certain conditions are met (45 CFR § 171.205).\\n\\n**Three (3) exceptions involve procedures for fulfilling requests to access, exchange, or use EHI:**\\n\\n1. **Content and manner exception** fulfilling a request to access, exchange, or use EHI in any manner requested or in an alternative manner, provided certain conditions are met, using (i) certified health IT specified by the requestor; (ii) content and transport standards specified by the requestor and published by the federal government or a standards-developing organization accredited by the American National Standards Institute; or (iii) an alternative machine-readable format, including the means to interpret the EHI, agreed upon with the requestor (45 CFR §171.301).\\n\\n1.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.nextech.com/blog/understanding-the-21st-century-cures-act\",\n      \"title\": \"Five Questions and Answers to Understanding the 21st Century Cures Act\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-05-01\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"[Ophthalmology](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/ophthalmology) | [Plastic Surgery](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/plastic-surgery) | [Compliance](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/compliance) | [Dermatology](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/dermatology) | [MIPS](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/mips) | [Regulatory & Compliance](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/regulatory-compliance) | [Orthopedics](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/orthopedics)\\n\\n### [2026 Changes to MIPS Reporting Criteria](https://www.nextech.com/blog/mips)\\n\\nBy: [Heather Miller Dongilli](https://www.nextech.com/blog/author/heather-miller-dongilli) | January 29th, 2026\\n\\n[](https://www.nextech.com/blog/how-to-prepare-for-a-cms-audit)\\n\\n[Ophthalmology](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/ophthalmology) | [Compliance](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/compliance) | [CMS](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/cms) | [Coding](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/coding) | [Clinical Efficiency](https://www.nextech.\\ncom/blog/topic/clinical-efficiency)\\n\\n### [A Step-by-Step Guide to Preparing Your Ophthalmology Practice for the New CMS Audits](https://www.nextech.com/blog/how-to-prepare-for-a-cms-audit)\\n\\nBy: [Courtney Tesvich](https://www.nextech.com/blog/author/courtney-tesvich) | November 21st, 2025\\n\\n[](https://www.nextech.com/blog/cms-meaningful-use)\\n\\n[Compliance](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/compliance) | [Meaningful Use](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/meaningful-use) | [EHR](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/ehr) | [Interoperability](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/interoperability) | [MIPS](https://www.nextech.com/blog/topic/mips)\\n\\n### [What Transitioning from Meaningful Use to Interoperability Means for Your Clinic](https://www.nextech.com/blog/cms-meaningful-use)\\n\\nBy: [Nextech](https://www.nextech.com/blog/author/nextech) | April 9th, 2025\\n\\n* [](https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https://www.nextech.com/blog/understanding-the-21st-century-cures-act \\\"Share on Facebook\\\")\\n* [](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Five+Questions+and+Answers+to+Understanding+the+21st+Century+Cures+Act&url=https://www.nextech.com/blog/understanding-the-21st-century-cures-act&via= \\\"Share on Twitter\\\")\\n* [](https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?url=https://www.nextech.com/blog/understanding-the-21st-century-cures-act&title=Five+Questions+and+Answers+to+Understanding+the+21st+Century+Cures+Act&summary=Nextech+answers+five+of+the+most+common+questions+about+the+21st+Century+Cures+Act.+With+the+deadline+looming%2C+here%27s+what+you+need+to+know+about+your+EHR. \\\"Share on Linkedin\\\")\\n* \\n\\n[https://f.hubspotusercontent00.net/hubfs/306056/assets/images/content/nextech-logo-svg.svg](https://www.nextech.com/)\\n\\n4221 W Boy Scout Blvd  \\nSuite 350  \\nTampa, FL 33607  \\n866\\\\.654.4396\\n\\n[](https://www.linkedin.com/company/nextech \\\"LinkedIn\\\") [](https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCbrzUm6uNnnm_NKUjGvj5Qw \\\"YouTube\\\") [](https://www.instagram.com/poweredbynextech/ \\\"Instagram\\\") [](https://www.facebook.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.foreseemed.com/blog/oncs-cures-act-final-rule\",\n      \"title\": \"ONC's Cures Act Final Rule: First Wave Begins\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2024-08-05\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"The key upgrade to the core data set is that EHR vendors must make clinical notes available via a structured data format and exchange those notes via APIs. This upgrade to the core data set makes it simpler for IT developers like [ForeSee Medical](https://www.foreseemed.com/) that use [NLP technology](https://www.foreseemed.com/natural-language-processing-in-healthcare) to read clinical notes, to obtain higher quality (no blurry faxes or scans) output. It also makes it easier for doctors, that may want to switch EHRs to export clinical notes from their legacy EHR and re-upload them into a different, new EHR.\\n\\n**Patients  \\n  \\n** APIs are the backbone of nearly every smartphone app. The Patient Access API will allow individuals to securely and easily obtain and use their electronic health information using the smartphone app of their choice.\\nWith more complete data in their hands, patients can be more informed decision makers, and take this information with them as they move from plan to plan, and provider to provider throughout the healthcare system.\\n\\n## The Way Forward\\n\\nThe final rule lays the foundation for modern day technology to meet the demands of patients and providers. It advances the needs of health care providers, while also being a huge step forward for patients. This industry shift will require a collaborative environment for both IT and business to work closely and quicken delivery. Understanding one’s readiness will help an organization define the interoperability approach needed to be compliant.\\n\\nForeSee-Medical-Logo-2020.png\\n\\nAt ForeSee Medical, we are tracking all of the latest standards. Our [HCC risk adjustment coding](https://www.foreseemed.com/hcc-risk-adjustment-coding) software was designed and built ready to exchange data that conforms with the 21st Century Cures Act mandate.\\n[Learn more](https://www.foreseemed.com/hcc-risk-adjustment-coding)\\n\\nBlog by: The ForeSee Medical Team\\n\\nCompliance , CMS Policy , Interoperability Steve Barth October 14, 2020 [Foresee Medical](http://maps.google.com?q=12555 High Bluff Drive San Diego United States)\\n\\n[Facebook 0](https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.foreseemed.com%2Fblog%2Foncs-cures-act-final-rule) [Twitter](https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.foreseemed.com%2Fblog%2Foncs-cures-act-final-rule&text=) [LinkedIn 0](https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&source=ForeSee+Medical+&summary=&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.foreseemed.com%2Fblog%2Foncs-cures-act-final-rule) [Reddit](https://www.reddit.com/submit?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.foreseemed.com%2Fblog%2Foncs-cures-act-final-rule) 0 Likes\\n\\nPrevious #### What is the Purpose of the Coding Intensity Adjustment?\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.himss.org/resources/final-onc-interoperability-regulation-what-you-need-to-know/\",\n      \"title\": \"Final ONC Interoperability Regulation: What You Need to Know\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"1. Resources\\n2. Final ONC Interoperability Regulation: What You Need to Know\\n\\nOn Monday, March 9, 2020, the [Office of the National Coordinator for Health IT (ONC)](https://www.healthit.gov/) and the [Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS)](https://www.cms.gov/) publicly released their final regulations related to driving more interoperability and data exchange across the entire healthcare ecosystem. The government intends the combined regulations to provide patients with timely access to their health data to make informed healthcare decisions and better manage their care. The Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) expects the regulations to place patients at the center of care delivery and provide them more control, which is the centerpiece of the Trump Administration’s work toward a value-based healthcare system.\\n\\nThe [ONC Interoperability and Information Blocking Final Regulation](https://www.healthit.\\ngov/curesrule/) implements key provisions of the [21st Century Cures Act](https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/34) focused on advancing interoperability; supporting the access, exchange, and use of electronic health information (EHI); and, addressing occurrences of information blocking. ONC’s regulation also establishes application programming interface (API) requirements using the Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources (FHIR®) standard, including for patients to use APIs to be able to electronically access all of their EHI, structured and/or unstructured, at no cost.\\n\\nThe CMS [Interoperability and Patient Access Final Regulation](https://www.cms.gov/files/document/cms-9115-f.pdf) builds on ONC’s Final Regulation as well as the [MyHealthEData Initiative](https://www.cms.gov/newsroom/press-releases/trump-administration-announces-myhealthedata-initiative-put-patients-center-us-healthcare-system) , which was originally announced at the HIMSS18 Conference.\\nThe CMS Regulation is focused on liberating patient claims data so patients can be more informed decision makers leading to better-informed treatment. More [information on the CMS Regulation](https://www.himss.org/news/final-cms-interoperability-regulation-what-you-need-know) can be found online.\\n\\n### The Key Parts of the ONC Regulation include:\\n\\n#### Certification Program-Related Changes\\n\\nONC sunsets the 2014 Edition and finalizes several changes to the existing 2015 Edition Health IT Certification Criteria, introducing some new certification criteria, revising existing certification criteria, and removing certification criteria. [ONC has summarized these changes online](https://www.healthit.gov/cures/sites/default/files/cures/2020-03/CuresUpdateOverview.pdf) .\\n\\nOverall, these changes constitute the 2015 Edition Cures Update.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2020/05/01/2020-07419/21st-century-cures-act-interoperability-information-blocking-and-the-onc-health-it-certification\",\n      \"title\": \"\\n      Federal Register\\n       :: \\n      21st Century Cures Act: Interoperability, Information Blocking, and the ONC Health IT Certification Program\\n    \",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2020-05-01\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"Published Document: 2020-07419 (85 FR 25642)\\n\\nThis document has been published in the _Federal Register_ . Use the PDF linked in the document sidebar for the official electronic format.\\n\\nDocument Headings\\n\\nDocument headings vary by document type but may contain\\nthe following:\\n\\n1. the agency or agencies that issued and signed a document\\n2. the number of the CFR title and the number of each part\\n   the document amends, proposes to amend, or is directly\\n   related to\\n3. the agency docket number / agency internal file number\\n4. the RIN which identifies each regulatory action listed in\\n   the Unified Agenda of Federal Regulatory and Deregulatory\\n   Actions\\n\\nSee the [Document Drafting Handbook](https://www.archives.gov/files/federal-register/write/handbook/ddh.pdf=9) for more details.\\n\\n###### Department of Health and Human Services\\n\\n###### Office of the Secretary\\n\\n1. 45 CFR Parts 170 and 171\\n2. RIN 0955-AA01\\n\\n# AGENCY:\\nOffice of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology (ONC), Department of Health and Human Services (HHS).\\n\\n# ACTION:\\n\\nFinal rule.\\n\\n# SUMMARY:\\n\\nThis final rule implements certain provisions of the 21st Century Cures Act, including Conditions and Maintenance of Certification requirements for health information technology (health IT) developers under the ONC Health IT Certification Program (Program), the voluntary certification of health IT for use by pediatric health care providers, and reasonable and necessary activities that do not constitute information blocking. The implementation of these provisions will advance interoperability and support the access, exchange, and use of electronic health information. The rule also finalizes certain modifications to the 2015 Edition health IT certification criteria and Program in additional ways to advance interoperability, enhance health IT certification, and reduce burden and costs.\\n\\n# DATES:\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://tldsystems.com/information-blocking-and-21st-century-cures-act\",\n      \"title\": \"Information Blocking and the 21st Century Cures Act | TLD Systems https://tldsystems.com › information-blocking-and-21st...\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"# Information Blocking and the 21st Century Cures Act\\n\\n* June 18, 2020\\n* By tahlia@tldsystems.com\\n* 0 Comments\\n\\n### Information Blocking and the 21st Century Cures Act\\n\\nby Dr. Michael Brody, DPM, CEO TLD Systems\\n\\nUnder the new law known as the 21st Century Cures Act, information blocking is now ILLEGAL. That means if you get a request from another provider for patient information, you are required to provide that information. The Office of Inspector General at OIG can investigate all claims of information blocking by providers and can levy fines and / or enforce Corrective Action Plans (CAP).\\n\\nThis rule applies to all Health Information including but not limited to:\\n\\n·        EHR information in certified software\\n\\n·        EHR information in non-certified software\\n\\n·        Digital Images\\n\\n·        Paper Charts\\n\\n·        Plain Films\\n\\n·        Any and all other patient health information\\nSo no matter how you keep your records, if you block the transfer of information you are in violation of this rule.\\n\\nDevelopers of Certified EHR technology can not place roadblocks or impediments to transferring information out of the EHR.  If a developer of certified software does not have tools to enable the transfer of patient information, they are considered an information blocker and can be subject to an investigation.\\n\\nWhat does this mean?\\n\\nFor Hospitals, in the past hospital systems have ‘closed’ their systems to people and hospitals outside their network and made it difficult for doctors who were not using the ‘preferred’ software platform or who were not on staff to obtain patient information. THIS IS information blocking. This has been a common practice in the past and will now be illegal. If you were using a system that was not the hospitals ‘preferred’ system and they said they would not connect with you, they will not be required to provide you with a connection.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.bignewsnetwork.com/news/278931519/6-major-healthcare-regulation-now-mandates-fhir-here-is-why\",\n      \"title\": \"6 Major Healthcare Regulation Now Mandates FHIR. Here Is Why\",\n      \"publish_date\": null,\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"**Who it applies to:** EHR developers, health IT vendors, providers, payers, anyone touching electronic health information (EHI).\\n\\nThe foundation of everything. The ONC Cures Act Final Rule established HL7 FHIR R4 as the national standard for health data access and created the information blocking prohibition. ONC-certified health IT must expose a FHIR R4 Patient Access API giving patients access to all their EHI at no cost. Organizations that interfere with EHI access face civil monetary penalties up to $1 million per violation.\\n\\n### 2\\\\. CMS-9115-F - Interoperability & Patient Access Final Rule (2020)\\n\\n**Who it applies to:** Medicare Advantage, Medicaid, CHIP managed care plans, and QHP payers on Federally-Facilitated Exchanges.\\n\\nThe first rule requiring payers to implement FHIR.\\nThree requirements went live in 2021: a FHIR R4 Patient Access API (claims, encounters, and clinical data available within one business day), a publicly available FHIR Provider Directory API, and Payer-to-Payer exchange of USCDI v1 data at patient request. If your payer organization is not live on these today, you are already out of compliance.\\n\\n### 3\\\\. ONC HTI-1 Final Rule - Deadline: March 1, 2026\\n\\n**Who it applies to:** All ONC-certified health IT developers and EHR vendors.\\n\\nThe most sweeping certification update in years. Health IT modules must upgrade to USCDI v3, over 80 data elements delivered via FHIR US Core Implementation Guide v6.1.0. The updated FHIR API criteria (170.315(g)(10)) also require SMART App Launch IG v2.0.0, including access revocation within one hour. FHIR Endpoints must be published in ONC-standardized formats.\\n\\n|**Enforcement Note**\\n\\nONC issued enforcement discretion extending the compliance date to March 1, 2026 (from January 1, 2026).\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://coephi.org/app/uploads/2023/07/21st-century-cures-act-final-rule-2023.pdf\",\n      \"title\": \"[PDF] 21st Century Cures Act Final Rule on Information Blocking - CoE-PHI\",\n      \"publish_date\": \"2023-07-21\",\n      \"excerpts\": [\n        \"**How the Information Blocking Rule applies to heightened**\\n\\n**privacy protections for substance use disorder and**\\n\\n**mental health treatment records.**\\n\\nThe 21st Century Cures Act aims to put patients in charge of their health records\\n\\nand promote interoperability by establishing penalties for healthcare providers\\n\\n(among others) who engage in information blocking. ONC’s Cures Act Final Rule on\\n\\nInformation Blocking prohibits healthcare providers from interfering with access,\\n\\nexchange, or use of electronic health information. ¹ However, it does not prohibit\\n\\nhealthcare providers from protecting information covered by a stricter privacy law,\\n\\nsuch as 42 CFR Part 2.\\n\\nFor more resources about the Information Blocking rule generally, see these resources\\n\\nfrom the Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology (ONC).\\n\\n**Key Point**\\n\\nThe Information Blocking rule does not require a healthcare provider to use or\\ndisclose electronic health information in a way that is prohibited under state or\\n\\nfederal privacy laws. ²\\n\\n**2023 update:**\\n\\nIn May 2023, ONC issued additional FAQs about how to interpret the Information\\n\\nBlocking Rule. Notably, the FAQs address how to interpret the Rule when another\\n\\nfederal privacy law requires that certain conditions be met prior to disclosure, when\\n\\nan individual requests that their EHI not be disclosed, and when an actor operates in\\n\\nmultiple states with differing privacy laws.\\\\*\\n\\n\\\\* See the ONC’s, Frequently Asked Questions.\\n\\nA Partnership\\n\\nFunded by Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration\\n\\n**21** **st** **Century Cures Act Final Rule**\\n\\n**on Information Blocking**\\n\\n**A Closer Look**\\n\\n**What does this mean for records protected by the federal privacy protections for**\\n\\n**substance use disorder treatment or for mental health records protected by state law?**\\n\\n• Providers should continue protecting records according to applicable law,\\n\\n...\\n\\nAdapted from 21st Century Cures Act: Interoperability, Information Blocking, and the ONC Health IT Certification Program\\n\\n(proposed March 4, 2019), 84 Fed. Reg. 7424, 7519, available at https://www.federalregister.gov/d/2019-02224/p-1226.\\n\\n7\\\\. 45 CFR 164.524(a)(1)(i).\\n\\n8\\\\. 45 CFR 164.524(a)(3)(i).\\n\\ncoephi.org\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"warnings\": null,\n  \"usage\": [\n    {\n      \"name\": \"sku_search\",\n      \"count\": 1\n    }\n  ],\n  \"session_id\": \"ses_0cba093c2ffeCsX4cK31TWSMpy\"\n}",
